<div id="content" class="container">
<div class="row"><div class="col-md-9"><h1 class="title">Paper Notes</h1>


<div id="outline-container-sec-1" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-1"><span class="section-number-2">1</span> Are Biological Systems Poised at Criticality?</h2>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-sec-2" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-2"><span class="section-number-2">2</span> Thermodynamics for a network of neurons: Signatures of criticality</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-2">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-2-1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-2-1"><span class="section-number-3">2.1</span> Introduction</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-2-1">
<p>
Want to find &ldquo;thermodynamic limit&rdquo; for neurons.
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-2-2" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-2-2"><span class="section-number-3">2.2</span> Theory</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-2-2">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>System of <i>N</i> elements, each element has state &sigma;<sub>i</sub><sub>nil</sub>, system state defined by &sigma;={&sigma;<sub>i</sub>,&#x2026;,&sigma;<sub>N</sub>).
</li>

<li>Standard thermodynamics apply.
</li>

<li>Want to estimate density of states, <i>n(E)</i>.
</li>

<li>Get entropy from density of states: \(S = ln(n(E))\)
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-sec-2-3" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-2-3"><span class="section-number-3">2.3</span> An Experimental Example</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-2-3">
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Extracted neuron firing counts from salamander visual center while it watched a movie
</li>
<li>Showed seemingly correlated clusters of neuron&rsquo;s firing.
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>






<div id="outline-container-sec-3" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-3"><span class="section-number-2">3</span> Temporal organization of ongoing brain activity</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-3">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-1"><span class="section-number-3">3.1</span> Introduction</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-1">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-1-1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-1-1"><span class="section-number-4">3.1.1</span> Stochastic process</h4>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-1-2" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-1-2"><span class="section-number-4">3.1.2</span> Study power structure</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-1-2">
</div><ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-1-2-1" name="sec-3-1-2-1"></a>See long range correlations, periodic oscillations<br ></li></ol>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-1-3" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-1-3"><span class="section-number-4">3.1.3</span> Study avalanche waiting times</h4>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-2" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-2"><span class="section-number-3">3.2</span> Ongoing activity: Temporal structure</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-2">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-2-1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-2-1"><span class="section-number-4">3.2.1</span> Activity is sequence of up-states</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-2-1">
</div><ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-2-1-1" name="sec-3-2-1-1"></a>Up-states last from 1ms ~ 100ms<br ></li></ol>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-2-2" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-2-2"><span class="section-number-4">3.2.2</span> Up-states generally not periodic</h4>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-2-3" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-2-3"><span class="section-number-4">3.2.3</span> Up-states seperated by periods of no activity (down-states)</h4>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-2-4" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-2-4"><span class="section-number-4">3.2.4</span> Up-states can be viewed as stochastic process</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-2-4">
</div><ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-2-4-1" name="sec-3-2-4-1"></a>R. Segev, B. Morris, E. Hulata, N. Cohen, A. Palevski, E. Kapon, Y. SHapira, E.B. Jacob, Phys, Rev. Lett. 88, 11(2002)&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;<span class="tag"><span class="badge Citation">Citation</span></span><br ></li></ol>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-2-5" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-2-5"><span class="section-number-4">3.2.5</span> Distribution of jumps between waiting times has been studied</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-2-5">
</div><ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-2-5-1" name="sec-3-2-5-1"></a>Jumps in sequence of wating times<br ><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-3-2-5-1">
<p>
The quantity &Delta;i=&Delta;t(i+1)-&Delta;t(i) where &Delta;t is the time between avalanches.
</p>
</div>
<ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-2-5-1-1" name="sec-3-2-5-1-1"></a>The distribution of &Delta;i is a symmetric Levy distribution<br ><div class="outline-text-6" id="text-3-2-5-1-1">
<p>
The probability density function of the LÃ©vy distribution over the domain x&ge; &mu; is:
f(x:&mu;,c)= \sqrt{c/2\pi} &times; e<sup>-c/2(x-&mu;)</sup>/(x-&mu;)<sup>3/2</sup>
</p>
</div>
</li></ol>
</li></ol>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-2-6" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-2-6"><span class="section-number-4">3.2.6</span> Distributions of waiting times &Delta;t=t<sup>i</sup><sub>j+1</sub>-t<sup>i</sup><sub>j</sub> is analyzed</h4>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-2-7" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-2-7"><span class="section-number-4">3.2.7</span> Rat cortical slices were studied</h4>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-3" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-3"><span class="section-number-3">3.3</span> Neuronal network model for ongoing brain activity</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-3">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-3-3-1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-3-1"><span class="section-number-4">3.3.1</span> Neuron update scheme:</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-3-1">
<p>
&nu;<sub>j</sub>(t+1)=&nu;<sub>j </sub>&plusmn; (v<sub>j</sub>&sdot;k<sub>out</sub>)/(k<sub>in<sub>j</sub></sub>) &times; (g<sub>ij</sub>)\(&sum;<sub>k</sub>g<sub>ik</sub>) 
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-3-2" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-3-2"><span class="section-number-4">3.3.2</span> Weight update scheme:</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-3-2">
</div><ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-3-2-1" name="sec-3-3-2-1"></a>If the connections were used:<br ><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-3-3-2-1">
<p>
g<sub>ij</sub><sub>nil</sub>(&tau;+1) = g<sub>ij</sub><sub>nil</sub>(&tau;) + |&delta;&nu;<sub>j</sub>(&tau;)|/&nu;<sub>max</sub>
</p>
</div>
</li>
<li><a id="sec-3-3-2-2" name="sec-3-3-2-2"></a>If the connections were not used:<br ><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-3-3-2-2">
<p>
&Delta;g = &sum;<sub>ij</sub>&delta;g<sub>ij</sub>/N<sub>B</sub>
Where N<sub>B</sub> is the number of non-zero connections
</p>
</div>
</li></ol>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-3-3" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-3-3-3"><span class="section-number-4">3.3.3</span> Up-down state dynamics</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-3-3-3">
</div><ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-3-3-1" name="sec-3-3-3-1"></a>Up states<br ><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-3-3-3-1">
<p>
When the avalanche strength (S<sub>&Delta;V</sub>) is less than a threshold, S<sub>&Delta;Vmin</sub>, the network remains in, or transitions to an  &ldquo;up state&rdquo; by resetting neurons to a depolarized value.
&nu;<sub>i</sub>(&tau;+1) = &nu;<sub>max</sub>[1-S<sub>&Delta;V</sub><sub>nil</sub>(&tau;)/S<sub>&Delta;Vmin</sub>]
</p>
</div>
<ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-3-3-1-1" name="sec-3-3-3-1-1"></a><span class="label label-primary TODO">TODO</span> Check different S<sub>&Delta;Vmin</sub>&rsquo;s<br ></li></ol>
</li>
<li><a id="sec-3-3-3-2" name="sec-3-3-3-2"></a>Down states<br ><div class="outline-text-5" id="text-3-3-3-2">
<p>
When the last avalache strength (S<sub>&Delta;V</sub>) is larger than a threshold, S<sub>&Delta;Vmin</sub><sub>nil</sub>, the network transitions into a &ldquo;down state&rdquo; by hyperpolarizing the neurons proportional to their previous activity.
&nu;<sub>i</sub><sub>nil</sub>(&tau;+1) = &nu;<sub>i</sub>(&tau;) - h&sdot;&delta;&nu;<sub>i</sub>(&tau;)
</p>
</div>
</li>
<li><a id="sec-3-3-3-3" name="sec-3-3-3-3"></a>Noise and driving terms<br ><ol class="org-ol"><li><a id="sec-3-3-3-3-1" name="sec-3-3-3-3-1"></a>Up states<br ><div class="outline-text-6" id="text-3-3-3-3-1">
<p>
In an up-state the noise is drawn from the interval d<sub>u</sub><sub>nil</sub>(&tau;+1)=[0,S<sub>&Delta;Vmin</sub>/S<sub>&Delta;V</sub><sub>nil</sub>(&tau;)]
</p>
</div>
</li>
<li><a id="sec-3-3-3-3-2" name="sec-3-3-3-3-2"></a>Down states<br ><div class="outline-text-6" id="text-3-3-3-3-2">
<p>
In a down-state, the noise has a small constant amplitude applied at a random site.
</p>
</div>
</li></ol>
</li></ol>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-sec-3-4" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-3-4"><span class="section-number-3">3.4</span> Temporal organization of avalanches</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-3-4">
<p>
The ratio R~h/S<sub>&Delta;Vmin</sub>&asymp; 10<sup>-4</sup> produces best replica of experimental results.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-sec-4" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="sec-4"><span class="section-number-2">4</span> The balance between excitation and inhibition controls the temporal organization of neuronal avalanches</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-4">
</div><div id="outline-container-sec-4-1" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="sec-4-1"><span class="section-number-3">4.1</span> Introduction</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-4-1">
<p>
Neuron timesteps are on the order of ~ 10ms
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
